<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="243" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1361,2036]" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,625,1433,1459]" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Remarks and differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
What lead us to believe that our material represented a new species was that, before comparing our specimens to the 
<typeStatus box="[665,768,1469,1495]" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">lectotype</typeStatus>
housed in 
<collectingCountry box="[896,995,1469,1495]" name="Belgium" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Belgium</collectingCountry>
, we first compared them to specimens identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[299,469,1505,1531]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andromache">
<emphasis box="[299,469,1505,1531]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. andromache</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Frederico Lencioni’s Collection in Jacareí, São Paulo State, collected in Bahia. In that comparison, we found that those specimens had significant differences in cercus, hind lobe of prothorax and shape of pterostigma, therefore they are described here as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilela &amp; Junior &amp; Furieri &amp; Lencioni" authorityYear="2021" box="[811,926,1578,1603]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeromei">
<emphasis box="[811,926,1578,1603]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. jeromei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In regard to overall morphology, the closest species to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilela &amp; Junior &amp; Furieri &amp; Lencioni" authorityYear="2021" box="[266,380,1614,1639]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeromei">
<emphasis box="[266,380,1614,1639]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. jeromei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<emphasis box="[410,586,1613,1639]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">
<taxonomicName box="[410,582,1613,1639]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andromache">L. andromache</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Despite their resemblance, there are many structures in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilela &amp; Junior &amp; Furieri &amp; Lencioni" authorityYear="2021" box="[1207,1320,1614,1639]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeromei">
<emphasis box="[1207,1320,1614,1639]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. jeromei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that allow us to differentiate these two species (
<taxonomicName box="[575,745,1649,1675]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andromache">
<emphasis box="[575,745,1649,1675]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. andromache</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in brackets): in dorsal view hind lobe of prothorax (
<figureCitation box="[1345,1428,1649,1676]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1331,193,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[256,1331,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male prothorax in lateral view: a—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; b—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL); male hind lobe of prothorax in dorsal view: c—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; d—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704352/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 2d</figureCitation>
) nearly straight at the middle (with a slight cleft, 
<figureCitation box="[686,766,1685,1711]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1331,193,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[256,1331,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male prothorax in lateral view: a—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; b—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL); male hind lobe of prothorax in dorsal view: c—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; d—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704352/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
), with blunt rounded corners (
<figureCitation box="[1102,1236,1685,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1331,193,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[256,1331,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male prothorax in lateral view: a—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; b—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL); male hind lobe of prothorax in dorsal view: c—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; d—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704352/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Figs. 2b, 2d</figureCitation>
) (with thin lateral projections, 
<figureCitation box="[291,427,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1331,193,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[256,1331,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male prothorax in lateral view: a—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; b—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL); male hind lobe of prothorax in dorsal view: c—Leptagrion andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; d—Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (holotype—FAAL)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704352/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Figs. 2a, 2c</figureCitation>
); pterostigma rhomboid (
<figureCitation box="[716,799,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[172,1418,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-17@2.[155,1433,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus: a—dorsal view of a lectotype of Leptagrion andromache Hagen in Selys, 1876 and paratype´s labels (IRSNB); b—lateral view of L. andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; c—lateral view of holotype of Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (FAAL); d—Comparison between Leptagrion andromache and Leptagrion jeromei forewing pterostigma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704350" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704350/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
, below) (quadrilateral, 
<figureCitation box="[1066,1149,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[172,1418,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-17@2.[155,1433,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus: a—dorsal view of a lectotype of Leptagrion andromache Hagen in Selys, 1876 and paratype´s labels (IRSNB); b—lateral view of L. andromache from Amapá state, Brazil; c—lateral view of holotype of Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (FAAL); d—Comparison between Leptagrion andromache and Leptagrion jeromei forewing pterostigma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704350" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704350/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
, above); cercus in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[222,302,1757,1783]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1377,1401]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,192,1341]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[154,1433,181,1353]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male Appendages: a—lateral view of a lectotype of Leptagrion andromache Hagen in Selys, 1876 (IRSNB); b—dorsal view (same specimen of a); c—lateral view of a paratype of Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (FAAL); d—dorsal view (same specimen of c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704354" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704354/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
) with a small, blunt, medial projection (with a more pronounced medial projection, 
<figureCitation box="[1260,1342,1757,1783]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1377,1401]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,192,1341]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[154,1433,181,1353]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male Appendages: a—lateral view of a lectotype of Leptagrion andromache Hagen in Selys, 1876 (IRSNB); b—dorsal view (same specimen of a); c—lateral view of a paratype of Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (FAAL); d—dorsal view (same specimen of c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704354" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704354/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 3a</figureCitation>
); cercus in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[328,410,1793,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1377,1401]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,192,1341]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[154,1433,181,1353]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male Appendages: a—lateral view of a lectotype of Leptagrion andromache Hagen in Selys, 1876 (IRSNB); b—dorsal view (same specimen of a); c—lateral view of a paratype of Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (FAAL); d—dorsal view (same specimen of c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704354" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704354/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 3d</figureCitation>
) distal tooth not reaching middle of cercus, blunt tips (distal tooth longer, reaching middle of cercus, acute tip, 
<figureCitation box="[378,461,1829,1856]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1377,1401]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,192,1341]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[154,1433,181,1353]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male Appendages: a—lateral view of a lectotype of Leptagrion andromache Hagen in Selys, 1876 (IRSNB); b—dorsal view (same specimen of a); c—lateral view of a paratype of Leptagrion jeromei spec. nov. (FAAL); d—dorsal view (same specimen of c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5704354" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5704354/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Fig. 3b</figureCitation>
). Apart from the morphology, coloration has also shown to be different among the two species, such as the postocular region with a transversal pale stripe (such stripe absent), and some paler areas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilela &amp; Junior &amp; Furieri &amp; Lencioni" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeromei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. jeromei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, due to the paucity of individuals of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilela &amp; Junior &amp; Furieri &amp; Lencioni" authorityYear="2021" box="[772,886,1902,1927]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeromei">
<emphasis box="[772,886,1902,1927]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">L. jeromei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we could not make further statements on coloration according to aging.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1361,2036]" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,450,1973,1999]" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Habitat and ecology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vilela &amp; Junior &amp; Furieri &amp; Lencioni" authorityYear="2021" box="[460,680,1974,1999]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeromei">
<emphasis box="[460,680,1974,1999]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="243">Leptagrion jeromei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was always collected associated with epiphyte bromeliads which indicates that, as the other congeners, this new species also breeds in phytotelmata.
</paragraph>
